{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e1d0f281-950c-4a1d-abec-ef35e8cc4fa6","content":"These are three distinct C# 15 breaking changes. Here's each one:\n\n---\n\n**1. SpanHelper.cs — Tightened ref-safety for spans in loops**\n\n`[x * 2]` assigned to `Span<int>` uses implicit `stackalloc` — its storage lifetime is scoped to the **loop body**. Assigning it to `results` (declared outside the loop) is now a ref-safety error because the pointee doesn't outlive the pointer.\n\n**Fix:** Use heap allocation:\n```csharp\npublic static int[] ProcessItems(int[] source)\n{\n    var results = new List<int>();\n    foreach (var x in source)\n        results.Add(x * 2);\n    return results.ToArray();\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n**2. Metadata.cs — `this` disallowed in `nameof` within attribute arguments**\n\n`this` is not available in attribute argument contexts. `nameof` doesn't evaluate anything — it only needs the member *name*, not an instance reference. C# 15 now enforces this properly.\n\n**Fix:** Drop `this`:\n```csharp\n[System.Obsolete(nameof(Endpoint))]\nvoid LegacyConnect() { }\n```\n\n---\n\n**3. Pipeline.cs — `with` parsing ambiguity in collection expressions**\n\n`with` is a contextual keyword (from `with` expressions on records). Inside a collection expression `[...]`, C# 15 now parses `with(x, y)` as the start of a `with` expression rather than a method invocation, creating a syntax error.\n\n**Fix:** Use a verbatim identifier to force it to be treated as a method name:\n```csharp\nobject[] items = [@with(x, y), z];\n```\nOr rename the method to avoid clashing with the keyword.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"aa5a4464-20e4-47ab-8818-6dd760c5f826","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about C# 15 / .NET 11 breaking changes. These are hypothetical future versions (as of my knowledge cutoff). Let me think about what I actually know and reason through each case.\n\nActually, let me think carefully. The user says they're migrating from .NET 10 / 